I&#39;ve now extended the `width=0` hack with the - let&#39;s call it - `displayIndex=0` hack. Works like a charm:

**Iteration 1**: We keep adding the columns as per our definition, so we don&#39;t need to refactor any code that relies on that column order: 

    foreach (ColumnDefinition cd in this.ColumnDefinitions)
    {
        ColumnHeader ch = new ColumnHeader();
        ch.Name = cd.Name;
        ch.Tag = cd;
        ch.Text = cd.Text;
     
        this.extendedListView.Columns.Add(ch);
    }

**Iteration 2**: To respect the users displaly-order, we modify the `displayIndex` as mentioned above, as soon as all columns are added to the listview: 

    foreach (ColumnHeader ch in this.extendedListView.Columns)
    {
        //DisplayIndex known?
        if (keyToIndex.ContainsKey(ch.Name))
        {
            int idx = keyToIndex[ch.Name];
            ch.DisplayIndex = idx;
        }
    }

Note: Columns the user has deselected don&#39;t have an display index stored in the configuration. So they now are floating around somewhere (with width 0), leading to the problem that they could be extended, when trying to extend another column.

**Iteration 3**:To overcome that issue, we just iterated another time, and pushed every invisible column to index 0. *No User should ever try to resize a column by clicking on the left side of the left-most column visible*:

    //Avoid inivisble columns (width 0) beeing stuck somewhere in between. 
    //push them all to the front, cause no one will try to expand the &quot;0st Column&quot;.
    foreach (ColumnHeader ch in this.extendedListView.Columns)
    {
        //DisplayIndex not known?
        if (!keyToIndex.ContainsKey(ch.Name))
        {
            ch.DisplayIndex = 0;
            ch.Width = 0;
        }
    }

